AGI – He was in the stoves from morning to evening, without ever having a break except to go to sleep in the accommodation that a large hotel on the Riviera Romagnola for which he worked had made available. His career as a young chef was crushed when, when he returned from an exhausting day of work, a piece of the ceramic sink in the bathroom was crushed on a hand causing him a lesion so as to force him to abandon his dream of becoming a chef.> The Court of Labour of Ravenna has recognized him a harm of 34 thousand euros underlining, explains to AGI his lawyer Francesco Chinni, that "the housing made available by the employer as part of the pay, constitutes to all effects an extension of the 'workplace with the consequent employer responsibility in the case of accidents".&nbsp; And, another important principle emerged from the judgment, “the Court of First Instance has customized the damage taking into account the age, the working past and the prospects it would have had without this incident.”
&nbsp;
Several co-workers of the cook had pointed out to their managers that the sink “cremmed in several points” would have been to be changed. “I intervened immediately after the accident and saw that he had the part of the torn arm – he told a witness -. The sink was broken, for a piece it was still attached to the wall, for another part it was on the ground all fragmented”. The worker stayed in one of the 400 rooms of the hotel whose managers said that the break of the washbasin would be to be charged to the "furia of the worker" who, read in the sentence, "have attempted to paint as a sort of fair in prey to frequent attacks of wrath".
&nbsp;
Disregarding the Court's reply: "As anyone can understand, there is more than one logical abyss between having discussed with a receptionist, even at a high voice, and putting down the washbasins of the bathroom, activity not even so easy to put into being."&nbsp; In increasing the recognised damage of 35% beyond what is usually referred to in the tables, the judge said he had considered that “the cooks work with the hands” and the “young age of the applicant at the time of the injury”.&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;
